{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19469"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19469"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.48,0.27,0.21,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84888"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12196"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30586"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84888"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with right forearm cellulitis. He has a history of recurrent abscesses and carbuncles on all four limbs requiring surgical drainage. He has no other medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right forearm shows a 4 x 3 cm area of cellulitis without fluctuance or abscess formation. He is prescribed oral clindamycin due to previous methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management to prevent recurrent infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mupirocin nasal ointment","Chlorhexidine body wash and mupirocin nasal ointment","Chlorhexidine body wash","Long-term prophylactic antibiotics","Oral probiotics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has recurrent MRSA skin infections requiring multiple surgical interventions. The most effective prevention strategy involves comprehensive decolonisation therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EChlorhexidine body wash and mupirocin nasal ointment\u003C/strong\u003E used in combination has been shown to be more effective than either agent alone in preventing recurrent MRSA infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMupirocin nasal ointment\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient as MRSA can colonise multiple body sites. While nasal colonisation is common, treating only this site may miss other areas of colonisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlorhexidine body wash\u003C/strong\u003E alone, while helpful in reducing skin bacterial load, is not as effective as the combination therapy. The nose remains an important reservoir for MRSA that needs to be specifically addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-term prophylactic antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are generally not recommended for recurrent MRSA infections due to concerns about developing antibiotic resistance. They may be considered in specific cases but are not first-line prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral probiotics\u003C/strong\u003E have not been shown to be effective in preventing MRSA skin infections. While they may have a role in preventing certain infections, there is no evidence supporting their use in MRSA prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of chlorhexidine body wash and mupirocin nasal ointment is typically prescribed for 5-7 days. Additional measures such as regular washing of bedding and clothes, maintaining good personal hygiene, and keeping any cuts or scrapes clean and covered are also important in preventing recurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Decolonisation therapy with both chlorhexidine body wash and mupirocin nasal ointment reduces recurrent MRSA skin infections.","Recurrent MRSA infections often require a combination of approaches including decolonisation and good skin hygiene.","Long-term antibiotic prophylaxis is generally not recommended for recurrent MRSA infections due to resistance concerns."],"references":["Westgeest AC, Hanssen JLJ, de Boer MGJ, Schippers EF, Lambregts MMC. Eradication of community-onset Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus carriage: a narrative review. Clin Microbiol Infect. 2025 Feb;31(2):173-181. doi: 10.1016/j.cmi.2024.01.003. Epub 2024 Jan 11. PMID: 38215977."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-12T16:47:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-12T16:49:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12196"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84888"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup